Newcastle disease - Australia (New South Wales)(07) 981124014045
Newcastle disease - Australia (update) 981009124616

[1
Date: Mon, 7 Dec 1998
Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: New Scientist, 4 Dec 1998
An Australian research finding, reported in the current issue of New
Scientist, is that the outbreak of Newcastle disease near Sydney two months
ago resulted from the mutation of a seemingly benign strain of NDV into a
virulent strain. The report, edited, is as follows:
"An outbreak of Newcastle disease, which can devastate poultry farms, has
provided virologists in Australia with a rare glimpse of how a supposedly
benign virus can turn into a killer.
"Thanks to quarantine controls, Australia had been free of the disease for
more than sixty years. But two months ago, it broke out near Sydney.
"We had assumed it had been brought in from overseas," says Jeff
Fairbrother, executive director of the Australian Chicken Meat Federation in
Sydney. But virologists with the Australian Animal Health Laboratory (AAHL)
in Geelong, near Melbourne, have now shown that the outbreak occurred when a
supposedly benign local strain of the Newcastle disease virus (NDV) mutated
into a virulent form.
"Allan Gould of the AAHL identified the virus as local by sequencing genes
from NDV taken from the dead chickens. The genes that code for two
glycoproteins carried on the surface of NDV included the code for a string
of nine amino acids found only in Australian strains of the virus.
"At the Fourth Asia Pacific Poultry Health Conference in Melbourne last
week, Gould told of when he realised a local virus had become a chicken
killer. Just as birds started dying on one farm, Gould was studying chickens
with throat lesions on a farm nearby. The sequence of the gene for one of
the glycoproteins, called the fusion protein, was identical to that in the
virulent form of NDV, except for two nucleotides.
"When the dead birds on the neighbouring farm were confirmed as victims of
Newcastle disease, Gould realised that this must have already happened.
Eventually around 10,000 chickens died, and another 100,000 were slaughtered
before the outbreak was brought under control.
"Research at AAHL has also implicated "benign" strains of NDV in a disease
that has claimed the lives of tens of thousands of chickens during the
1990s. Late respiratory syndrome had been blamed on "Escherichia coli" and
other bacteria. But in a report to appear in the "Australian Veterinary
Journal" next month, veterinary pathologist Peter Hooper shows that
bacterial infections can only get a foothold if NDV has already created
lesions in chickens' throats."
