[3
From: "Dr. David E. Swayne" <dswayne@arches.uga.edu>
Date: Tue, 8 Dec 1998 15:22:35 -0500

I have heard the same story recently via e-mail; before the conference in
Australia.
If Gould is right in his analysis, this is the first well documented case
of a low virulent NDV mutating to a high virulent form and causing an
outbreak. The previous outbreak viruses segregate in highly virulent and
lower virulent lineages.
I would like to see some more data or at least the publication before
accepting this concept. Even if this is true for the current Australian
outbreak, this may be the exception instead of the rule in NDV biology.
---
David Swayne
USDA/ARS Poultry Research Laboratory
Athens, GA, USA
***
[4
Date: Wed, 9 Dec 1998 09:07:01 GMT
From: dalexander.vla@gtnet.gov.uk (Dennis Alexander)

This is the official line from AAHL, that the virus mutated from low to high
virulence.
We have recently received the viruses and will hopefully confirm their
findings. This is not the first report of probable mutation from low to high
virulence; see:
ALEXANDER, D.J., CAMPBELL, G., MANVELL, R.J., COLLINS, M.S., PARSONS, G. &
McNULTY, M.S. (1992) Characterisation of an antigenically unusual virus
responsible for two outbreaks of Newcastle disease in the Republic of
Ireland in 1990. Veterinary Record 130, 65-68.
COLLINS, M.S., FRANKLIN, S., STRONG, I, MEULEMANS, G. & ALEXANDER, D.J.
(1998). Antigenic and phylogenetic studies on a variant Newcastle disease
virus using anti-fusion protein monoclonal antibodies and partial sequencing
of the fusion protein gene. Avian Pathology 27, 90-96
---
Dennis Alexander,
FAO Newcastle Disease Reference Laboratory,
MAFF Central Veterinary Laboratory,
New Haw, Weybridge, UK
[During an epidemic one can pick up changes. During the 1970-72 ND epidemic
in the UK which was a virulent pneumo-encephalitic form, I remember Bill
Alan telling me in 1971 that he had reports of three neighbouring flocks in
East Anglia with severe enteric disease but subsequently it quickly reverted
back. As a caveat, there is a tendency in NDv genetics to sequence short
(e.g., 108bp). We have found that it is more revealing to sequence longer
(e.g. 389 bp) the F gene. By the way, AAHL is the Australian Animal Health
Laboratory -- their Pirbright / Plum Island / CVL. Amusingly it was
originally the Australian National Animal Health Laboratory, but ANAHL
phonetically is a bit embarrassing - Mod.MHJ
